The Nevada Commission on Tourism sponsors a promotion where visitors can stop at several designated locations along the route and request a state issued novelty passport with a stamp representing that location. Visitors can mail-in the completed passport and receive a certificate, signed by the Governor, certifying they survived The Loneliest Road in America. The word survived is a tongue-in-cheek reference to the Life article, which quoted an American Automobile Association spokesperson as saying, We warn all motorists not to drive there unless they're confident of their survival skills.
In the 20 years that have passed since the article was published, US&nbsp;50 has gained popularity among people desiring a scenic or less traveled alternative to Interstate 80 in Nevada Interstate 80 across Nevada. This increase in popularity has caused some to dispute that US&nbsp;50 still deserves the title of The Loneliest Road in America.cite web
 url=http://www.sfgate.com/cgi-bin/article.cgi?f=/c/a/2004/03/28/CMGKD5Q8UB3.DTL
