History
Lincoln Highway
Image:Hwy50Nevada.jpg thumb The eastern junction of US&nbsp;50 and US&nbsp;93 at Majors Place
In Nevada, US&nbsp;50 was built mostly along the route of the Lincoln Highway, the first transcontinental highway in the United States, formed in 1913.cite web
 url = http://www.fhwa.dot.gov/infrastructure/lincoln.cfm
 title = The Lincoln Highway
 publisher = Federal Highway Administration
 last = Weingroff
 first = Richard F.
 accessdate =2009-01-21 This route had been previously used by the Pony Express, an early attempt at an express mail service, started in 1860. The Pony Express used the technique of riders changing horses at stations approximately convert 10 mi km  apart to maximize speed. Some of the towns along US&nbsp;50 were founded as Pony Express stations.cite web
 url = http://www.stjosephmuseum.org/ponyexpresshistory.php
 title = The Pony Express History
 publisher = St. Josephs Museums Inc.
 acceddate = 2009-03-21 The original numbered designation of this route, which appeared on Nevada Highway maps as far back as 1919, was State Route&nbsp;2. Route&nbsp;2 had an alternate branch, Route&nbsp;2A, corresponding to a split in the Lincoln Highway near Fallon.cite web
 url = http://www.lincolnhighwayassoc.org/info/nv/
 title = The Lincoln Highway in Nevada
 publisher= Lincoln Highway Association
 accessdate = 2008-03-13 The main and alternate branches of Route&nbsp;2 are reversed from the modern routings of US&nbsp;50. Mainline Route&nbsp;2, the Donner Party Donner Branch, terminated at Fernley along modern US&nbsp;50 Alternate. State Route&nbsp;2A, the Pioneer Branch, followed mainline US&nbsp;50, terminating at Carson City. State Route&nbsp;2, and the Lincoln Highway, used a different routing between Ely and Salt Lake City, Utah from the modern routes. The original routing used what is now U.S. Route 93 Nevada US 93 from Ely to the ghost town of Schellbourne, Nevada Schellbourne and then dirt roads towards Tooele, Utah.cite web
 url = http://www.nps.gov/poex/planyourvisit/auto_nv.htm
 title = Auto Tour route - Nevada Pony Express
 publisher = National Park Service
 accessdate=2008-03-13cite web
 url=http://www.patricepress.com/books/580.htm
 title=1924 Map of the Lincoln Highway
 publisher=Lincoln Highway Association republished by Practice Press
 author=Lincoln Highway Association
 accessdate=2008-03-13
Image:Nvclubelynv.JPG thumb left Downtown Ely, Nevada Ely
In 1926, when the U.S. Highway system was announced, there was a gap in US&nbsp;50 between Ely and Thistle, Utah.cite map
  publisher=U.S. Department of Agriculture
  title=w:Image:1926us.jpg United States System of Highways
  year=1926
  accessdate=2008-03-03
  accessmonth=03
  accessyear=2008
 At the time, the states of Utah and Nevada were feuding about which of the old auto trails would be paved and used for the new U.S. Highway system. Utah officials refused to pave the portion of the Lincoln Highway west of Salt Lake City. They perceived this route as being expensive to build, with no benefit for the state. Nevada officials, and the Lincoln Highway Association, pleaded with Utah authorities to change their position, even offering funds to help offset the additional cost of paving that route. However, Utah favored the Victory Highway modern Interstate 80 Nevada Interstate 80. The Lincoln highway directed travelers destined for both southern California southern and northern California on a route away from Utah cities, towards central Nevada. The Victory Highway was a shorter, more direct route, that only directed traffic for northern California out of the state.cite web
 url = http://historytogo.utah.gov/salt_lake_tribune/in_another_time/120593.html
 title = The Long And Winding Road  The Lincoln Highway: Utah Played A Key Role In Taming West For Cars
 last = Schindler
 first = Hal
 publisher = State of Utah
 date = 1993-12-05
 accessdate = 2009-01-21 The choice not to pave the Lincoln Highway would direct travelers bound for southern California to use the Arrowhead Trail auto trail Arrowhead Trail modern Interstate 15. This route serves numerous communities in Utah, but only Las Vegas, Nevada Las Vegas and few other small towns in Nevada. The final blow to the original route of the Lincoln Highway was the formation of the Dugway Proving Grounds, a military base used for weapons testing, which closed the area to the public. The Lincoln Highway was re-routed to Salt Lake City along a circuitous route via Wendover, Utah Wendover and the Bonneville Salt Flats.
cite book
   last = Patrick
   first = Kevin J.
   coauthors = Wilson, Robert E.
   title = The Lincoln Highway Resource Guide
   publisher = Indiana University of Pennsylvania
   location = Indiana, Pennsylvania
   chapter = 15-Lincoln highway in Utah
   page = 203
 This route was initially numbered US&nbsp;50 from Ely to Wendover and U.S. Route 40 US&nbsp;40/50 across western Utah, but has been renumbered US&nbsp;93, U.S. Route 93 Alternate Nevada US 93 Alternate and I-80.
Route changes
Image:Middlegatenv.JPG right thumb The Middlegate roadhouse
Most of modern US&nbsp;50 was pieced together from several routes designated as Nevada State Routes in the early 1900s. The portion from Lake Tahoe to Carson City was originally a portion of Nevada State Route 3 State Route 3. The original designation for US&nbsp;50 from Carson City to Ely was Route&nbsp;2 and 2A. East of Ely was originally numbered Route 7 to the modern junction with US&nbsp;93 and Route 14 from there to the Utah state line.cite web
 url =http://www.nevadadot.com/traveler/maps/historical/
 title = Historical Maps 1927 and 1952
 publisher = Nevada Department of Transportation
 accessdate = 2009-01-28
The modern route of US&nbsp;50 has significantly changed since the highway was first commissioned in 1926. The biggest change is between Ely and Green River, Utah. The first contiguous route of the highway between these cites followed the modified routing of the Lincoln Highway to Salt Lake City. The highway returned to Green River along what is now numbered Utah State Route 201 UT 201, U.S. Route 89 Utah US 89, and U.S. Route 6 Utah US 6. The route was changed when the more direct route between these cities via Delta, Utah was paved. The 1954 edition of the Nevada highway map was the first to show the new routing.
Previously, the road to Delta consisted of unpaved state routes. The paved route did not follow the exact route of the old dirt roads. The improved route bypassed the ghost town of Osceola and entered Utah approximately convert 14 mi km sigfig=2 to the south of the dirt road. The border crossing was moved to facilitate an easier route across western Utah. In Utah, the old road traversed a difficult route through Marjum Canyon, while the paved route followed a simpler path along the north shore of Sevier Lake.cite map
 publisher  = Benchmark Maps
  title      =Utah Road and Recreation Atlas
  year       = 2002
  scale      = 1:170000
  pages       = 57
  section    = G7
  isbn       = 0-929591-74-7
 url=http://www.benchmarkmaps.com
Image:Saltwells.JPG thumb left Salt Wells, just east of Fallon, Nevada Fallon
Three different routes have existed between Lake Tahoe and Carson City, Nevada Carson City. The original, used by the Lincoln Highway, was previously known as Johnson's Cutoff or the Carson Ridge Emigrant Road. This route, which followed Kings Canyon to scale the Sierra Nevada U.S. Sierra Nevada,cite web
 url = http://nevadaculture.org/shpo/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=214&Itemid=9
 title = Spooner Summit, Nevada Historical Marker 261
 publisher = Nevada Department of Cultural Affairs
 accessdate = 2009-02-18 was severely damaged by a flood in 1997.cite web
 url = http://nevada.usgs.gov/crfld/data_byflood_1.cfm
 title = USGS Flood Chronology of the Carson River Basin
 publisher = United States Geological Survey
 accessdate = 2009-03-16 The U.S. Forest Service still promotes this road for its historical value, but has announced that it will no longer be maintained and travel is only recommended by foot, horse or four wheel drive vehicle.cite web
 url = http://www.fs.fed.us/r4/htnf/recreation/arch_hist/kings_canyon_road/kings_canyon_road.shtml
 title = Kings Canyon Road
 publisher = United States Forest Service
 accessdate = 2009-03-16 A portion in the lower part of the canyon inside Carson City limits is still maintained by the state as Kings Canyon Road Nevada State Route 512 SR 512. In 1923, while still known as State Route 3, the road to Lake Tahoe was changed to follow Clear Creek Canyon, along a path that had been used for a series of tunnels and flumes, to transport timber from Lake Tahoe to the Virginia and Truckee Railroad depot in Carson City.cite book
 url = http://books.google.com/books?id=LT54rVzP_RAC
 pages = 174-177
 title = Nevada Trails West Region: Backroads & 4-Wheel Drive Trails
 last =  Massey
 first = Peter 
 co-author = Wilson, Jeanne;  Titus, Angela
 chapter = 24- Spooner Summit Trail
 isbn = 1930193157
 publisher = Adler Publishing
 date = 2008
The iteration is now known as Old Clear Creek Road. Only a small portion of Old Clear Creek Road is maintained by the state as unsigned Nevada State Route 705 SR 705, the remainder is an access road for private residences in the canyon. The modern route, also using Clear Creek Canyon, was built in the late 1950s.
US&nbsp;50 was rerouted through the eastern half of Fallon. The original route is not drivable as it runs through Naval Air Station Fallon; portions are still in public use as Harrigan Road Nevada State Route 115 SR 115 and Berney Road Nevada State Route 119 SR 119.cite web
 url = http://www.forgottennevada.org/sites/lincoln_more.html
 title = Fallon, Nevada - Nevada DOT
 publisher = Nevada Department of Transportation hosted by forgottennevada.org
 date = 1934
 accessdate = 2009-02-18  Around 1967, US&nbsp;50 was improved between Middlegate and Austin, to bypass steep grades and sharp curves over Carroll Summit. The original route is now Nevada State Route 722 SR 722.cite map
  publisher  = H.M. Gousha Company
  title      =Road Atlas hosted by Broer Map Library
  url        =http://www.broermapsonline.org/members/NorthAmerica/UnitedStates/Southwest/gousha_ra_1967_030.html
  year       = 1967
  pages       = 45
  accessdate = 2008-01-27
  accessmonth= 01
  accessyear = 2008
 A freeway bypass, Interstate 580 Nevada Interstate 580, is under construction around Carson City. When finished, US&nbsp;50 will be rerouted concurrency road concurrent with I-580 and the downtown route will be renumbered Nevada State Route 529 SR 529 and Nevada State Route 530 SR 530.
